               <p>JAMES McCLEERY. I live at Belfast. I was opposite <placeName id="t18270712-178-crimeloc980">Westminster Abbey</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18270712-178-crimeloc980" type="placeName" value="Westminster Abbey"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18270712-178-crimeloc980" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270712-178-off978 t18270712-178-crimeloc980"></join> last Sunday, about three o'clock; I had a handkerchief in my coat pocket, and was not aware of any thing till a person behind told me I had lost it - the prisoner rushed by me at that moment, and I followed him, and saw him drop my handkerchief, which my wife took up and gave to me.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. Did you see me take it? A. No.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270712-178-person949">
                  THOMAS 
                  MILLER
               <interp inst="t18270712-178-person949" type="surname" value="MILLER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270712-178-person949" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270712-178-person949" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a bricklayer. I saw the prisoner running, with a yellow silk handkerchief - I saw him take it from somewhere; I think it came from a pocket.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. Could you see me take it, when you were two yards before me? A. I was exactly opposite you.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. It was thrown in my face by some person who ran by - I caught it and went to run; that gentleman stopped me.</p>
               <p>Eleven Witness gave him a good character.</p>
